The irradiance spectrum of the lamp used for VL PD studies is given in Fig. S6. The photocatalytic activity of P25 and P25/C-dot are evaluated using the VL PD of RhB, MO (Fig. 5
                        ) and 4CP (Fig. S7). The VL PD (Fig. 5A) by P25 is 49% while it is 80% for P25/C-dot, which is a 60% increase. The photoactivity of P25/C-dot, is further tested using MO, which is a dye known for its stability and resistance towards PD and have minimal contribution from the dye sensitization mechanism due to its blue-shifted λ
                        max (460 nm) compared to that of RhB. The PD of MO shows a 20% increase for the composite (40% at 120 min) compared to that of the control P25 (33%) (Fig. 5B). The higher PD activity of P25/C-dot is a clear indication of the contribution of C-dot. The VL absorption of C-dot shall be attributed as one of the reason for the improved PD property of the composite and further studies are conducted as an attempt to understand the role of C-dot and the mechanism of PD reactions.

In an attempt to understand the PD mechanism, the reactions are carried out in the presence of scavengers such as t-BuOH which is a scavenger of •OH; NaN3, that of both •OH and 1O2 and BQ that of O2•−, respectively. The percentage contribution of scavengers in the VL PD of RhB by P25/C-dot are given in Fig. 6
                        A. In the presence of t-BuOH, NaN3 and BQ, the PD values, by P25/C-dot, are 52.5, 37 and 62.2% (Fig. 6B), respectively. This is indicating the suppression of PD in the presence of scavengers. The percentage of •OH, 1O2 and O2•− are estimated as 34, 20 and 22% (Table 1
                        ), respectively. The remaining unaccounted PD% (∼20%) might be due to the direct attack of RhB by holes or/and by other ROS such as peroxides or hydrogen peroxides, formed by the secondary reactions of primary ROS. The scavenger study results for the PD of RhB by P25 are given in Fig. S8 and the percentage contributions of ROS are given in Table 1. The ROS percentages are different from that of the composite with •OH, 1O2 and O2•− being 6, 1 and 28%, respectively. The unaccounted contribution, which amounts to ∼65% shall be attributed to other ROS (which are not the focus of this study) formed by secondary reactions. This indicates that the primary ROS (O2•−) formed by P25 is not a potential ROS for attacking RhB due to its lower redox potential and hence, it instead undergoes secondary reactions to form other ROS. A small percentage (6%) of •OH in P25 may be due to the rutile phase in P25 which can absorb a small portion of the VL and produce holes in the VB of P25.
